You say that to an older piglet.
talistosekien hn knn tol- t tu teatiseki k lil te ps nan kskola talistosekien kontake
When what happens as a piglet?
Well you know that just when they're born they are as small as little puppies, right?
li- lil tenn mak kaatisekimansik hti ania tetiseki nakne k- kmpa nal tn
Have you ever seen piglets getting born? When they drop out, one by one?
k n tetiseki nan k pa pan poklpokl nal t
Have you seen piglets being born?
te- tatiseki mak seki nan k papan
I just saw the little ones.
When they are tiny, just born, when they are suckling haging on their mother's udder.
ttk- tklak hl te kmpa nan kstl kia mak emi mak ts mkm mak psteki mak tolati hnn k
So then they are tiny, like little puppies.
knan ktekinn tokolak htuke teti kaati sekikti toman hn ke
So with that, you know in the past,
nowadays they don't have the 'thongse/tose/' (pig stalls), right?
jot jos- jotmn iln tip tisintinn ite tos- teati tose hekne antilwamstanh tosi
But back in the days with our thatched-roof houses, they were everywhere.
knti enale tokatip hl ten ta isstuke
Every house had one, you would go there to do your business, you know.
k tosika ta iss kti kaknea mak k pntu pokok
Well then the pigs would eat that, you know.
kmn mak teti mkkuk he nasieke
So then, when you keep them like that,
k hm till temn ite tetika
here wasn't there a dog in that house where you passed?
jo joti kaati intike jo ap tipe kaati isti ania
When they get about that big,
you call them that way, when they take off their 'talisme/jalisme/'.
talistosekien konta i talismeka psn tom k-
So when they are past that tiny size and have become a middle-sized pig.
kkika tokolak hn k ps nan tokm tustosekika testen he
"Oh, it's shed off that 'talisme/jalisme/', it's a 'talistoseki/jalittoseki/'."
But, so you say 'shed off the 'talisme/jalisme/''?
'talisme/jalisme/' means that the piglet is growing to become a more middle-sized pig.
talismeen hn kn tom tukan tiki kanten hnn k
It means it shed off the 'young appearance'.
k lin ksi ps tisten hnn mal ituke
It means that the 'piglet period' has passed for them, and they got a little bigger now.
- lin knn iten nm kako tom kka- ksten hnn soli
So if it was a human, like, a little child?
kenan inkan aimn hsl jk- jka nan k?
Like a two, or three-year old child.
t hn tu- tu- tu sl se sl ten kiktiluk
So a piglet that has shed off its 'talisme/jalisme/'...
"like a piglet that has shed off its 'talisme/jalisme/' with that smooth skin, it's pretty, isn't it?", you can say.
talis- talismetoseki- talisme psin tosekikti mentlak hn ke kopta
Ah this is how you say it?
But why is a piglet that has shed off its 'talisme/jalisme/' smooth?
kenti musa talisme psin tosekika mentlak he
Well, you know, rather than when it's young,
ka k lil te potan inte
you know like when it gets middle-sized and when children get prettier when they grow,
tukan tiki te tokom a- kitl k kamin ep tits mak

you know they grow prettier, smiling all the time, right?
Well then, pigs too, their fur gets all smooth and the black thingies become pretty.
kmn inte teatitu k tltu mak mentlak hku mak skama hn ke mak koptuke
Then you say that this child, like a piglet that has shed off its 'talisme/jalisme/',
kmn iten tali- talisme psinn tosekikti i kitu
"Oh this smooth thingy, it shed off its 'talisme/jalisme/', it's getting prettier."
eiku mentlak hn ke koptak he kamst talisme psn
So you say it that way?
Yes, this is how the old people say it.
ktiluk ke mak halmatli k kltuke
So when you say it this way,
[younger] people don't have a clue of what you're talking about and...
t misik misin malsantito ala titi mos hen
So our grandchild, a girl, she's sixteen now, so,
knan uli sontinn titipai sonti inte jljss ituke hnane
"Oh your face, the skin is so smooth and beautiful", I say,
eiku lkuli pipuka mentlak hene konan hnan
"Mum, what does that [word for smooth] mean?"
So not even the word for 'smooth' she knows?
k mentlak hten han malto mola
I said "mentlak/, that means that your skin is beautiful", so
mentlak hnn k mentlak hn kn ke j i pipuka jepten hnn mal hnane ite
she said "mum, what does that mean? What does it mean, 'it shed off its 'talisme/jalisme/' "?
ma tal- k musin mal talisme psinn k musin soli
Well of course she doesn't understand, so,
when it comes to you, "wow, this kid here, there's nothing he doesn't know",
nin aiku jain tal alan molnn k si
t- tetu satuli pewa nonan i
"he knows it so well", I said.
moln k si tal anten hm mak k he issie
So my daughter said, "tell him that, what you just said!"
So I learnt it well then!
Well this is what we've grown up hearing so often from old people!
me ulin jesnalput k tlta halmatlapi tlta k ptin mal inan
I think I learnt it quite well.
And now I've got to learn one more thing!
inte to to hna pewa tiko
tal- il- talistoseki kolane tukanestosekituke hsl
A pig that is passed the baby stage.
Ah one that passed the baby stage?
ki nma san ktuke ki nm-
So the babies, what do you call them?
Well, like two or three-year olds, aren't they little toddlers, they can't walk properly and such.
ki - lin kitl hn se sl tu sl ten kitl lin ki anika mak kltito mot hku mak
Well yeah, the pigs too, when they get at that age,
kmn tosekitu k te temin hsl iten j
once they've got off they mother's teats you would sell them on the market, you know.
m tt mknn k iten t timn iten tae ka mak pola nastuke

What do you call it before that?
Before that you just call it a piglet.
k tnenn kia k lin - tosekiseki
So after that, what comes after that?
k tam talistas- toseki tamn misikka
"Let's go buy a pig!" you'd say.
You know, nowadays you'd say [teadi], but we say [toegi].
tatien hti ania ite kenti toseki
In the past, that's what people would say.
Back in the days you would go to the market, right,
You would raise them and then sell them, you know.

So once you've sold them you'd go buy the middle-sized pigs on the market.
pla pulmn iten to ite k tukanstoseki sale kann kla tae
So then the ones you buy at the market are called 'talistoseki/'.
ite kk ka sa onn k talistoseki
You'd put them in baskets [to carry them home].
With a net bag on top.
ue kumul maali j sakne mak satane
You would put them into the tose/,
and raise them - did you see such things, where you would have a tose/?
tilunn k kln k pa nan jesnal k tose hnti
Well I did see one, but
But you didn't see people raising pigs, right?
Well over there there is a place where they do that, but
Where, you mean, in the folk village?
So you saw it in such a place?
So are there steps on such a tose/ as well?
knn misin tosieto j kaitani isin k
in order to do your business there would be stones put on top of each other, and you would crouch on either side of the whole to do it.
k jopn pokesili ite tol- tollu ta ilhke saknea joki mak kum tolpke j tali jatake j anta sa nastuke
So then, on the pile of rocks?
No not on the pile, just on the flat surface.
sanstemilo ani kia mesak hke atakne kia tali j-
No not with stones, so you would have the stones for the outer wall, and wood.
tollu ani ka na- tollu jatoke samn namu
And with stones you build that, too.
If with stones, with flat ones.
I mean somehow you need to able to get on top of it, onto the tose/, right?
t hesa k utle kasa hnn k anika tosie
So now if you have the stones like this,
you would build it this way, right? Then it's closed into these directions, so then,
i ik j sahl k ani? kem ite ilutu maka tiku jolutu maka timn iten
and in order for a whole to be in the middle.
ite jo jo kauntika t tike
i jatoki jotuluk ma- j- jo jolohke
So if you do it this way, if there is a whole in the middle,
so you would sit on it,
and then the pigs would come in this way and eat the feces.
hmn teatin ilu tl wa mak to mkkuk
It worked that way, you know.
Ugh back in the days we used to do it that way.
The pigs would grow eating dung.
mak tetika to mk k nasie
Well then, the other people in the village see that...
k hmn tn salamt- tn ml salamtli ta ponnti
In all of the Jeju region we used to have that.

if you go to do your business,
so the feces, whether it is urine or feces, the swine would eat it.
pn pntu kia kkis otumiko pniku ta kki he- mite pomn teatika ta mk
if you use that toilet, can't other people see you?

No, you would do in a way that people can't see you.
ani anpokeklum hekne j htuke j
So you would use stones to surround them in a way that it shields off the view.
tollu ta kaliknea anpo- salaml anpoikeklm j kamtewa
So if you go to that side where you have the tose/,
teati tose hnntin j n han toke kakne hemin to
you would build a little roof, or with stones.

sometimes if you have it roofed then you wouldn't get wet under the rain,

but in places where it's completely open,
if you don't have anything to cover yourself from the rain,

Ugh if I think about how we used to live in the past...
